text: I've been using ChatGPT to decompress after hard shifts. Just... typing what happened and having something respond. It helps more than I expected.
Cooked dal and rice at midnight after a 14-hour shift. The smell made the apartment feel like home for 30 minutes.
Diagnosed a tricky case today — caught a PE that three of us had initially missed. The attending pulled me aside and said 'good catch.' I replayed it for hours.
Paid off one of my smaller loans — $4,200 gone. Cried at my kitchen table. Positive cry.
Looking at my schedule for next month. I have 4 nights on call. I'm already tired just looking at it.
My co-resident Priya is getting married. She seemed so happy talking about it. I felt happy for her and also just... far away from that version of life.
Three hours off in the afternoon. Slept. That was the right call.

Patient died today. 67, lung cancer, family at bedside. I held it together in the room. Cried in my car in the parking garage.
First yoga class in four months. Spent most of it crying silently. The instructor didn't say anything. That was kind.

A patient asked me today if I love my job. I said yes. I think it was mostly true.
I used to have hobbies. I used to paint watercolors. My kit is still in a box I never unpacked.
